    {
        "author": ".vbuterin",
        "category": "Channel Graveyard",
        "parent": "",
        "content": "In addition to adding a Merkle root of code to the account object, we can add a Kate commitment to code",
        "created_at": "2020-08-26T03:17:57.750000+00:00",
        "attachments": null
    },
    {
        "author": ".vbuterin",
        "category": "Channel Graveyard",
        "parent": "",
        "content": "See https://dankradfeist.de/ethereum/2020/06/16/kate-polynomial-commitments.html on Kate commitments",
        "created_at": "2020-08-26T03:18:25.128000+00:00",
        "attachments": null
    },
    {
        "author": ".vbuterin",
        "category": "Channel Graveyard",
        "parent": "",
        "content": "The powerful advantage of Kate commitments is that you can make an O(1) sized witness (really! just 48 bytes) for an arbitrary, even non-contiguous, subset of the code",
        "created_at": "2020-08-26T03:18:58.887000+00:00",
        "attachments": null
    },
    {
        "author": ".vbuterin",
        "category": "Channel Graveyard",
        "parent": "",
        "content": "They do require a trusted setup, which is why I would favor adding them in addition to Merkle roots, so clients can choose which type of witness they want",
        "created_at": "2020-08-26T03:20:16.236000+00:00",
        "attachments": null
    },
    {
        "author": "s1na",
